{"key":"processedPost-8148544","value":{"id":8148544,"first":8148479,"last":8148996,"when":1205585433,"utime":"03/15/08 03:50 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>shevanel said:</b><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br />yeah, it has a gauge, and i just put the stopper on <br /></blockquote><br /><br /><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/thumbup.gif\" alt=\":thumbup:\" title=\":thumbup:\"/> I put the stopper on from the jump. Bring heat up from medium setting, not full throttle. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />Not quite.<br /><br />Allow the steam to vent for a few minutes before putting the weight/stopper on.<br /><br />Start the process with the stove on <i>high</i>.&nbsp; There is no reason to heat the water slowly-it wastes time.&nbsp; When the water boils, steam will begin escaping the vent.&nbsp; Allow the steam to vent for five minutes before putting the weight on.&nbsp; When 15 psi is reached, reduce the stove setting to the minimum setting that will maintain 15 psi.&nbsp; <br /><br />Don't allow excessive rattling of the weight as this boils water out of both the PC and the individual jars.&nbsp; Adjust the stove setting so you have 15 psi, with very little rattling of the weight.&nbsp; Maintain that 15 psi for sixty to ninety minutes, and then shut off the stove burner.&nbsp; <br /><br />The next morning after all has cooled, remove the jars.&nbsp; If you prepared the grains properly, there is no reason to shake jars while hot.&nbsp; They'll shake very easily when cool.<br />RR","title":"Re: Using PC for first time....","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}